  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Published by Peter Lang Verlag in 2018, Tracey Wilen-Daugenti's <em>Digital Disruption</em> has found its most tangible footprint outside the formal citation record, circulating through commercial book channels and a small but notable collection of public-facing video appearances. With three recorded scholarly citations and strong commercial visibility, the book sits at the intersection of practitioner-oriented discourse and emerging academic interest in technology's social and organizational consequences.</p>\n\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The book's most prominent signal is its commercial reach. Its presence on both Amazon and Goodreads indicates that <em>Digital Disruption</em> was positioned and received as a trade-accessible scholarly work, reaching audiences beyond the typical institutional library circuit. This commercial linkage is reinforced by five YouTube videos in which Wilen-Daugenti discusses the book's themes \u2014 appearances spanning her own channel, a mortgage industry platform, and mainstream television coverage including ABC 7 Los Angeles and a government affairs program. These media engagements, concentrated largely around the book's 2018 release year, suggest an active public communication strategy and genuine interest from practitioners in sectors navigating technological change.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">Formal scholarly uptake, while modest in absolute terms, places the book in the 76th percentile of comparable works, indicating that its citation performance is stronger than most publications in its cohort. The three citing works arrived at spaced intervals \u2014 2019, 2021, and 2022 \u2014 suggesting a slow but sustained rather than purely coincidental pattern of engagement. Citing venues include a Cambridge University Press monograph and an economics working paper series, and the citing authors work across disciplines ranging from post-humanist philosophy to organizational learning and ICT management. This disciplinary spread points to the book's relevance as a reference point for writers grappling with broad questions of technological dynamism, knowledge obsolescence, and institutional adaptation.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">Library cataloging data further contextualizes the book's intended audience. WorldCat subject headings \u2014 covering internet social aspects, information technology, and leadership \u2014 reflect the book's bridging character between technical and managerial literatures. Confirmed library holdings remain limited in the available data, which, combined with the book's stronger commercial than institutional footprint, suggests it was designed to reach decision-makers and reflective practitioners as much as academic researchers. The Chicago School appears among affiliated institutions in the citing network, lending a faint but present educational sector thread to its uptake.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">Taken together, the evidence portrays <em>Digital Disruption</em> as a work with genuine public and professional resonance that has begun to attract measured scholarly notice. Its citation trajectory \u2014 dispersed across formats including a book and two book chapters, and engaging themes from pandemic-era systemic disruption to workforce obsolescence \u2014 reflects the broad applicability of its core argument. The book's impact to date is best characterized not by citation volume but by the diversity of contexts in which scholars and practitioners have found it worth acknowledging, a pattern consistent with practitioner-bridging scholarship in rapidly evolving technology fields.</p>",
